OpenEO Platform - User Story 4¶

On-demand processing of Sentinel-2 data:¶

  • ARD compliant
  • With custom parametrization
  1. Visualize on-demand Sentinel-2 data, EODC (Force) Vito (iCor,smac).
  2. EODC has terrain correction with Force. Show differences between Force (has terrain correction) and iCor in mountain areas. Same area as before maybe.
  3. Visualize performance/measure time when bbox over two tiles and compare when only above one tile.
  4. Visualize metadata

Step 2 - openEO graph creation for Sentinel-2 L2A¶

We will request the same area from two back-ends, VITO and EODC, which will process the data with iCor, and Force¶

  1. Open the connection with VITO and EODC back-ends. Please use the openeo-auth tool to configure credentials. https://open-eo.github.io/openeo-python-client/auth.html#config-files-and-openeo-auth-helper-tool
In [24]:
vito = openeo.connect("https://openeo-dev.vito.be").authenticate_basic()

eodc = openeo.connect("https://openeo.eodc.eu/v1.0").authenticate_basic()
  1. Define the process graph for VITO (iCor) for loading the data, applying the atmospheric correction and save the result.
In [10]:
collection      = 'SENTINEL2_L1C_SENTINELHUB'
spatial_extent  = {'west':bbox[0],'east':bbox[2],'south':bbox[1],'north':bbox[3]}
temporal_extent = ["2018-07-22", "2018-07-24"]
bands           = ["B02","B03","B04","B08","CLM",'B09','B8A','B11','sunAzimuthAngles','sunZenithAngles','viewAzimuthMean','viewZenithMean']

s2_l1c_vito = vito.load_collection(collection,spatial_extent=spatial_extent,bands=bands,temporal_extent=temporal_extent)
l2a_icor = s2_l1c_vito.atmospheric_correction(method='iCor').filter_bands(["B02","B03","B04"]).reduce_dimension(reducer="mean", dimension="t").save_result(format="GTIFF")
  1. Repeat the graph definition for EODC (Force)
In [11]:
collection      = 'boa_sentinel_2'
spatial_extent  = {'west':bbox[0],'east':bbox[2],'south':bbox[1],'north':bbox[3]}
temporal_extent = ["2018-07-22", "2018-07-24"]
bands           = ["band_2","band_3","band_4"]

s2_l2a_eodc = eodc.load_collection(collection,spatial_extent=spatial_extent,bands=bands,temporal_extent=temporal_extent)
l2a_force = s2_l2a_eodc.reduce_dimension(reducer="mean", dimension="t").save_result(format="GTiff")
  1. Visualize the openEO process graph.
In [12]:
l2a_icor.to_graphviz()

  1. Create a new batch job on the VITO back-end and ask to process it.
In [13]:
job_vito = vito.create_job(l2a_icor.graph)
job_id_vito = job_vito.job_id
if job_id_vito:
    print("Batch job created with id: ",job_id_vito)
    _ = job_vito.start_job()
else:
    print("Error! Job ID is None")

From the previous output, you may notice that the back-ends use different projections: VITO uses the UTM Zone 32 (EPSG:32632) whereas EODC uses EQUI7. This is much clearer if we look at the images in their projected grid.

In [34]:
fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(20,20))

brg_vito = tone_mapping(s2_vito_icor[2],s2_vito_icor[1],s2_vito_icor[0])
ax1.imshow(brg_vito,cmap='brg')

brg_eodc = tone_mapping(s2_eodc_force[1],s2_eodc_force[2],s2_eodc_force[0])
ax2.imshow(brg_eodc,cmap='brg')
Out[34]:

If we add the data over the map as new layes, they will be both reprojected to WGS84 (EPSG:4326) and therefore they will overlap.

In [35]:
addLayer(eoMap,'./data/US4/s2_eodc_force.tif','eodc',clip=[0,1800])
addLayer(eoMap,'./data/US4/s2_vito_icor.tif','vito',clip=[0,1800])
eoMap.map
